<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnian Croat on Defending Croat Enclaves </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401195494 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 1830 
GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0401195494 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Muslim forces are continuing to bring in 
reinforcements and equipment in the Lasva Valley and are 
stepping up troop movements, which leads to the conclusion that 
a new offensive in this area is in the offing. This is reported 
by the Political Department of the Croat republic of 
Herceg-Bosna's defense ministry. [passage omitted] 
  At a news conference today, Jadranko Prlic, the prime 
minister of the Croat republic of Herceg-Bosna, reiterated the 
demands contained in the Croatian Government's letter on the 
overall reassessment of relations with the Muslim leadership in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. He justified this by saying that 
Izetbegovic is continuing the Muslim offensive against the 
Croat-populated areas in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  He stressed that the Muslim leadership has stolen from the 
other two peoples everything that made Bosnia-Herzegovina an 
internationally recognized state. All Bosnia-Herzegovina 
consulates in the world are purely Muslim. Mr. Prlic cited the 
example of the so-called Bosnia-Herzegovina Embassy in Zagreb, 
where all 127 employees are of Muslim nationality. The world is 
beginning to realize that Izetbegovic is an aggressor, not a 
victim. Is the evacuation of Croats from central Bosnia being 
planned, a foreign correspondent asked Mr. Prlic. The reply was 
emphatic: 
  [Begin Prlic recording] As I said in my introductory 
address, 
we shall defend those regions at any cost. Vitez, Busovaca, 
Novi Travnik, part of the Travnik municipality -- the 
Owen-Stoltenberg plan envisages these areas as a constituent 
part of the Croat republic of Herceg-Bosna. Therefore, we will 
do all we can to defend these areas. [end recording] 
  We had to pay a bloody price for our alliance with the 
Muslims, but despite everything, we are ready to negotiate with 
both the Muslims and the Serbs. The international boundaries of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina have been clearly defined, while the internal 
ones depend on how large an area can be defended, Jadranko Prlic 
pointed out. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

