<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serb Commander: UN Troops Safe in Serb Areas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401170994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1528 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0401170994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zvornik, 4 Jan (TANJUG) -- Major General Milan 
Gvero, deputy commander of the main headquarters of the republic 
of Srpska's Army [VRS], told TANJUG today that not one UN 
Protection Forces [UNPROFOR] member has ever been hurt on 
Serb-held territory. At the same time, Gvero added, it is well 
known how many UNPROFOR troops have lost their lives or have 
been wounded in Muslim and Croat-controlled areas. 
  "Facts point to the inevitable conlusion that the Blue 
Berets 
are completely safe only on the territory of the republic of 
Srpska," Gvero stressed. According to him, "the Serbian side 
has so far displayed full cooperation in its dealings with 
members of international organizations and UNPROFOR." Gvero 
underlined that UNPROFOR's movements are always determined by 
previous agreement between the two sides and that, because of 
this, "there is absolutely no reason why the Serb side should be 
singled out as the party obstructing or preventing UNPROFOR's 
movements." 
  The deputy commander of the VRS main headquarters pointed 
out 
that top-level officers recently met General Francis Briquemont, 
UNPROFOR's commander for Bosnia-Herzegovina, and that "it was 
noted with mutual satisfaction that a high degree of rapport has 
been established between the Serbian side and UNPROFOR." 
  "We expect soon to have a similar meeting with General Jean 
Cot, UNPROFOR's commander for former Yugoslavia, which will 
certainly be mutually beneficial," General Gvero assessed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

