<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Finland Approves Humanitarian Aid Package </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P20188Z Helsinki HELSINGIN SANOMAT in Finnish 23 Dec 93 p 9 </F>
<F P=103> 94P20188Z </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki HELSINGIN SANOMAT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Finnish </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Finnish News Service report: "Forty Million Markkas in </F>
Humanitarian Aid From Finland to Bosnia"] 
  [Text] Finland has granted 40 million markkas in 
humanitarian assistance to Bosnia-Herzegovina. The aid will be 
handled through the Foreign Ministry's Development Aid Section. 
  "Planning for distribution of the aid will start in January. 
The aid will partly consist of goods, partly personnel, and 
partly as direct support," said Humanitarian Aid Section Chief 
Ritva Jolkkonen. 
  Needs for the aid will be discussed with international 
relief 
agencies. This year aid has gone through the UNHCR (United 
Nations Office of the High Commissioner for Refugees), the 
International Red Cross, and the World Health Organization (WHO). 
<H5>  Partly Goods, Partly Money </H5>
  Part of the aid will go as goods, part as money, since at 
its 
destination money is needed for purchasing fuel, etc. The aid 
sent through WHO will be in the form of medical equipment and 
such items as artificial limbs. Finnish experts can also be sent 
to Bosnia-Herzegovina with the aid money. "The intention is to 
act now in anticipation of winter needs," Jolkkonen stated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

