<H3> <TI>   Daily Reports Losses Suffered in Agriculture </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0501154994 Prague CTK in English 1205 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0501154994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague Jan 4 (CTK) -- Losses in Czech agriculture 
in 1993 can be roughly estimated at between 8.1 and 8.3 billion 
crowns (about 275,000 USD), the daily HOSPODARSKE NOVINY writes 
today. The data, obtained from the director of the Research 
Institute for Agricultural Economics, Josef Kraus, resulted from 
the institute's analysis and are preliminary. 
  Of the loss, 4.14 billion crowns was generated by state 
farms 
and 2.24 billion crowns by agricultural cooperatives. Private 
farmers showed the best results: They showed a profit when 
compensation for the work of the farmer and family members are 
not included. 
  Businesses involved in agricultural primary production saw a 
loss of 384 million crowns, while other agricultural companies, 
such as school farms, ended up with 1.2 to 1.4 billion crowns in 
aggregate losses. 
  Debts owed by the farms worsen the situation. They total 
42.2 billion crowns, more than twice the amount of claims -- 
19.7 billion crowns. 

</TEXT>

