<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Budget Envisages More Money for Agriculture </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401200494 Warsaw PAP in English 1857 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401200494 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Jan 4 -- The 1994 draft budget law envisages 
more means for subsidies lowering interest on agricultural 
credits, intervention measures on the agricultural market and 
for the development of countryside infrastructure, Deputy 
Agriculture Minister Maria Zwolinska said Tuesday [4 January]. 
Under the draft budget, the amount allocated for subsidies to 
agricultural credits is to be increased by nearly 70 percent as 
compared with 1993. Cheap credits are to be granted to farmers 
for the purchase of fertilizers, pesticides, seeds and for other 
expenses facilitating the reconstruction of agricultural 
production. 
  The upgrading of farms and the food processing sector is to 
be supported by the agency for the restructuring and 
modernization of agriculture in line with a law adopted by the 
Sejm. Funds at the agency's disposal are to come from budget 
subsidies, interests on bank reserves and repayments of credits 
granted by the agency's predecessor -- the fund for agricultural 
restructuring and debt-rescheduling. Some 1.2 trillion zlotys 
(47 million USd) from a World Bank loan are to be earmarked for 
the development of countryside infrastructure. 

</TEXT>

