<F P=101> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Letter of Intent to IMF Outlines Goals </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0301171394 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1604 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0301171394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest ROMPRES, 3/1/1994 -- The Romanian 
Government plans to withhold on a line of cautious fiscal, 
monetary, and budgetary policies in 1994 and 1995, says the 
letter of intent and the memorandum for the following two years 
agreed with the International Monetary Fund. The letter was 
forwarded by the prime minister [Nicolae Vacaroiu] to parliament 
for debate and approval. 
  The said policies will be implemented through a package of 
measures of structural reform including an accelerated 
privatization and restructuring of the enterprises, deep reforms 
of the fiscal and financial sector, and the establishing of a 
inter-bank currency market. 
  The memorandum of economic policy contains details of these 
policies aiming to achieve the economic goals of the government. 
The Romanian Government requests a 19-month stand-by agreement 
with the IMF to make available 131.95 million special drawing 
rights [SDR] plus two drawings totalling 377 SDR [figure as 
received], half of which within the structural transformation 
facility and following the approval of the memorandum, with the 
other half available by the date of the finalization of the 
first assessment by the IMF scheduled for 15 November 1994. The 
second assessment is scheduled for 15 May 1995. The first 
assessment is expected to outline the macro-economic, budgetary, 
and monetary objectives for 1995 and to reassess the estimations 
for external financing needs. 

</TEXT>

