<F P=101> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Small Privatization Returns Estimated </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0401142794 Prague CTK in English 1207 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0401142794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague Jan 4 (CTK) -- Overall returns from small 
privatisation, which was completed on December 31, 1993, reached 
35.1 billion crowns (over one billion USD) [U.S. Dollars], 
National Property Fund Chairman Tomas Jezek says in today's 
issue of the daily CESKY DENIK. A total of 3.9 billion crowns 
of that have thus far been spent. Administrative costs such as, 
for example, those for privatisation commissions, were 240 
million crowns, while 450 million crowns was spent on 
depreciated property returned to its original owners. 
  Settlement of liquidation consequences of state-owned 
companies have thus far demanded close to 2 billion crowns. 
Town councils obtained a one-time payment of 1.2 billion crowns 
as compensation for enterprises which represented income for 
local budgets and were privatised or restituted. The net 
balance from the process is 31.2 billion crowns, of which 20 
billion has been deposited long-term, the interest of which is 
to be used in the privatisation of health care, Jezek concluded. 

</TEXT>

