<H3> <TI>   Spokesman on NATO Membership, Russian View </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0401105894 Warsaw PAP in English 1030 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0401105894 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Jan. 4 -- Poland's search for membership of 
NATO is motivated by a wish to create a more stable security 
situation in Europe, and should not be interpreted as a threat 
to Russia, presidential press spokesman Andrzej Drzycimski said 
on Tuesday. 
  In an interview for the third programme of Polish Radio, 
Drzycimski noted that the former communist bloc was the main 
region where conflicts and wars are emerging. 
  Drzycimski also welcomed the statement on Monday from 
General 
John Shalikashvili, chief of the United States General Staff, 
that Russia will not be granted the right of veto over the 
eventual entry of central European states into the Atlantic 
alliance. Until now, it had seemed as though it was not NATO 
that would decide on accepting or rejecting new members, but 
Russia, Drzycimski said. 

</TEXT>

