<H3> <TI>   Hungarian Minority Leader on `Special' Region </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0401165994 Prague CTK in English 1623 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0401165994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava Jan 4 (CTK) -- Chairman of the 
Egyutteles Hungarian minority movement in Slovakia, Miklos 
Duray, today confirmed that the Komarno meeting convened by the 
Hungarian parliamentary parties in spite of the reservations 
raised by the Slovak president, government and parliament is 
aimed at creating a "region with special legal status" in 
southern Slovakia. 
  Egyutteles respects the laws and the Constitution and does 
not seek the revision of the state borders with Hungary, Duray 
said, adding that his movement wants to strive to ensure rights 
for the Hungarian minority only as a legal part of the Slovak 
Republic. It is only by coincidence that the Komarno meeting 
will take place on the eve of U.S. President Bill Clinton's 
meeting with the presidents of the Visegrad countries in Prague, 
Duray said. 
  Egyutteles demands that the ethnic principle is taken into 
account while introducing the new territorial division of 
Slovakia, he said, adding that his party intended to propose 
that the Komarno meeting appeal to the Slovak parliament to 
ratify the European Parliament Charter of European Towns and 
Regions. The Slovak Republic has not yet joined this agreement. 

</TEXT>

