<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus Calms Russian Fears on NATO Growth </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501234394 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1900 
GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0501234394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In contrast to the small countries of Central Europe 
and those in the area that still continue to split up, Russia is 
a great power as far as the United States and other NATO members 
are concerned. It is a country with which they are having to 
reckon. Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus has declared this in 
reaction to the remark made by Russian President Boris Yeltsin, 
who today called on NATO member countries to disperse Russia's 
fears that they have adopted a duplicitous attitude on this 
issue. 
  Yeltsin also warned against the negative reaction of the 
Russian public in case the bloc is expanded. He described the 
arguments of those countries striving to gain entry into NATO as 
unconvincing. Prime Minister Klaus is conscious that Russia 
regards this to be a sensitive issue. However, there is no need 
for fear yet because, as the prime minister has said, no one has 
offered us NATO membership. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

