<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus on Planned Talks of Visegrad Four </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501224294 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1730 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0501224294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1730 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Czech cabinet discussed in Prague today 
technical details of the visit to Prague next week of U.S. 
President Bill Clinton and an increase in the number of police. 
Our Prague correspondent, Daniela Galikova, attended the ensuing 
news conference and filed the following report: 
  [Galikova] Replying to a question from Slovak radio, Czech 
Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus confirmed the planned talks with 
Slovak Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar as well as with the prime 
ministers of Poland and Hungary, which will take place after the 
talks with the U.S. President. On the evening of 12 
January--that is, after the U.S. President departs--the Czech 
president, prime minister, and foreign minister will give 
dinners. According to Prime Minister Klaus, the presidents of 
Slovakia, Poland, Hungary, and the Czech Republic will dine at 
the Castle, the prime ministers of these countries will dine at 
Prime Minister Klaus's invitation in Lichtenstein Palace, and 
the foreign ministers will dine at the Czech Foreign Ministry. 
  Responding to another question concerning the summit, Prime 
Minister Klaus stressed that, right from the beginning, as soon 
as President Clinton's intention to visit Prague was announced, 
the Czech Republic did not doubt that it would use the meeting 
for holding talks with the representatives of the Visegrad Group 
countries. At no time was it considered that only we would be 
holding talks or that the talks would be held collectively, the 
Czech prime minister stressed. He thus reacted to some reports 
carried by both the domestic and foreign press that the Czech 
Republic did not support the idea of joint talks between the 
representatives of the Visegrad Group and the U.S. President. 

</TEXT>

