<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Briquemont Gives Reasons for Departure </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0501161194 Paris AFP in English 1557 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0501161194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, Jan 5 (AFP) -- UN Protection Force 
[UNPROFOR] commander General Francis Briquemont, who is leaving 
the job earlier than expected, has not been forced out but asked 
to quit because he is tired, UNPROFOR spokesmen said Wednesday. 
  The Belgian general's departure "is absolutely not linked 
with any disciplinary measure," said UNPROFOR's Sarajevo sector 
spokesman Lieutenant-Colonel Guy de Battista. 
  UNPROFOR spokesman Major Idesbald van Biesebroeck said 
Briquemont would leave Sarajevo at the end of January. "He is 
tired. I can understand his feeling of tiredness, because it's 
quite clear that he is not so young anymore. 
  "After seven months of this difficult mission he should be 
tired," he told a press conference. 
  De Battista added: "General Briquemont's return is happening 
under normal conditions and at his request," describing as 
"completely unfounded" rumours about the reasons for 
Briquemont's departure. 
  Van Biesebroeck said Briquemont had asked to leave via the 
normal channels. "He asked his minister of defense, who goes to 
the minister of foreign affairs who goes to secretary general. 
It is an ordinary diplomatic procedure," he said. 
  Belgian Defence Minister Leo Delcroix confirmed on Tuesday 
that Briquemont was leaving ahead of his mandate, which was due 
to last until July. Meanwhile the British Defence Ministry said 
Wednesday that British General Michael Rose will replace 
Briquemont. Rose is currently British Army chief of staff. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

