<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Kosovo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Group Urges Return to Normalcy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0501162794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1513 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0501162794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pristina, Jan 5 (TANJUG) -- The Association of 
Albanians, Serbs and Montenegrins for a United Serbia and 
Yugoslavia on Wednesday called on the ethnic Albanians in 
Kosovo-Metohija, especially intellectuals, to raise their voice 
against extremists and encourage their fellow countrymen to 
return to normal studies and work and building a common life in 
this Serbian province. 
  In a statement to the public, the association warned of "the 
disastrous results of the policy of extremist Albanian political 
parties" in Kosovo-Metohija, manifested in the mass quitting of 
jobs, schools and university. This policy has deprived a whole 
generation of young Albanians of proper schooling. 
  On the other hand, leaders of extremist Albanian parties and 
war profiteers secured a good life for themselves and their 
children, usurping for themselves the benefits that belong to 
all in the province. They therefore have no moral right to 
speak on behalf of all Albanians, said the statement. 
  The separatist ethnic Albanian leadership, which advocates 
Kosovo-Metohija's secession from Yugoslavia and joining it to 
neighboring Albania, exerts constant pressures on its fellow 
countrymen to disregard the laws of Serbia and the Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia, to leave their jobs and refuse to pay 
taxes. 
  Succumbing to these pressures, a majority of ethnic 
Albanians 
boycotted the 1990, 1992 and 1993 elections. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-49212 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu001__a94001" </HT>


