<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aid for Muslims Passes Through Serb Territory </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601203494 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1939 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0601203494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zvornik, Jan 6 (TANJUG) -- More than 30 vehicles 
with 256 tonnes of humanitarian aid headed for the Moslem 
enclaves in war-torn Bosnia-Herzegovina and parts of Sarajevo 
under Moslem control freely passed Thursday through the 
territory of the Bosnian Serb Republic (RS). 
  According to Bosnian Serb military sources in Zvornik, on 
the 
border with Yugoslavia where the cargo controls are made, 13 
trucks of the UN High Commisioner for Refugees (UNHCR) have 
taken 72 tonnes of flour to Tuzla, north-east 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. The International Committee of the Red 
Cross has taken 61 tonnes of flour and 35 tonnes of family food 
parcels to the same city. 
  Srebrenica, the Moslem enclave in eastern Bosnia, has 
received 78 tonnes of flour and 10 tonnes of heating oil, and 10 
tonnes of heating oil have been sent to the medical center in 
Zvornik. 
  The international humanitarian organisation Duga from Skopje 
has sent three trailers with food and medicine to be distributed 
to both the Moslem and Serb-controlled parts of Sarajevo. 
  The delivery of humanitarian aid to the civilian population 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina has been hindered for months due to fierce 
Moslem-Croat fighting in the central and southern parts of the 
republic in which a war between local Serbs, Croats and Moslems 
has been raging since April 1992. During all this time the only 
safe way for the convoys is through the territory under Bosnian 
Serb control. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

