<H3> <TI>   Zieleniec on Clinton's Visit, `Open' NATO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601133594 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1300 
GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601133594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Minister of Foreign Affairs Josef Zieleniec spoke at 
a news conference in Prague today on the coming visit to Prague 
of U.S. President Bill Clinton. He said that its program could 
be seriously changed by the death in the family of the U.S. 
President. Despite this, it is envisaged that the first day of 
the talks will have a bilateral Czech-U.S. character, while the 
second day of the visit will be devoted to consultations with 
representatives of other Visegrad countries. 
  As to the much discussed question of our relation toward 
NATO, Josef Zieleniec said: 
  [Begin Zieleniec recording] The fact is that we are 
seriously 
discussing with our Western partners, and thus also with the 
United States, our future membership, and we are expecting a 
statement saying that NATO is an open alliance. [end recording] 
[passage indistinct] 

</TEXT>

