<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Chairman of Left Bloc on Clinton Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601164894 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1400 
GMT 6 Jan 93 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601164894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The viewpoint on the coming visit of U.S. President 
Bill Clinton to Prague was published by the Left Bloc today. 
Jaroslav Ortman, deputy chairman of the party, said the 
following: 
  [Begin Ortman recording] The changed situation in Europe, we 
are convinced, should lead toward seeking new paths to solving 
questions of security and not toward using [word indistinct] 
patterns. It is obvious that the policy of the U.S. Government 
and the United States, presented by the "Partnership for Peace" 
plan, is in the incipient stage. 
  The path of the Left Bloc does not lead via the expansion of 
NATO. We have registered the words of Prime Minister Klaus 
saying that membership of the Czech Republic in NATO is not 
topical. No one wants us there anyway at the moment. 
  We see a solution in the system of collective security and 
not in the existence of a military pact of a part of Europe, 
whether big or small. We are convinced that, particularly in the 
sphere of seeking paths of collective security, Czech foreign 
policy should be much more active. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

