<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik Pleased With `Historic' Israel Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601205594 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1730 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601205594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1730 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] A Slovak Government delegation led by Minister of 
Foreign Affairs Jozef Moravcik left Israel for Cyprus by air 
this morning. Here is our special correspondent Agata Stanekova 
reporting from Nicosia: 
  [Stanekova] Let us begin with the delegation's visit to 
Israel, which ended today. Minister of Foreign Affairs Jozef 
Moravcik, speaking to journalists aboard the plane today, said 
that pursuing a well-balanced policy in the entire region was an 
important issue for Slovakia. The visit was meant to send a 
clear signal, saying that the Slovak Republic wants to continue 
the process of deepening relations with Israel in every sphere, 
and we understood the visit as the first stage in realizing this 
fundamental aim, Jozef Moravcik said. 
  During the flight to Cyprus, I also asked Slovak Minister of 
Economy Jan Ducky to assess the visit. 
  [Begin Ducky recording] I am convinced, and this view was 
shared by our Israeli partners, that this was a historic visit 
because at long last we were able to normalize relations between 
Israel and Slovakia. This fact is of great importance for 
entrepreneurs and bankers in both countries because at last we 
can start working on the basis of direct contacts without 
middlemen and third parties. This should be reflected in both 
the extent of our cooperation and its effectiveness. 
  I think the visit was very useful. Participating were not 
only members of the government delegation but also 15 
entrepreneurs from almost all spheres of industry and a strong 
delegation representing the banking circles, led by National 
Bank of Slovakia Governor Masar. [end recording] [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

