<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army `Explanation' for Albanian Citizen's Death </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601113694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1059 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 6 Jan (TANJUG) -- In connection with a 
statement issued by the Albanian Ministry of Foreign Affairs, 
which was broadcast by several foreign news agencies from Tirana 
regarding frequent incidents that have taken place along the 
Yugoslav-Albanian border, the information service of the General 
Staff of the Yugoslav Army has issued the following explanation: 
  "Border units of the Yugoslav Army have been strictly 
observing the rules of border service, and all incidents in 
which people who were illegally crossing the border were either 
caught or killed have taken place on the territory of the 
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia. 
  "This has always been established by interstate commissions 
following investigations. 
  "Members of the Yugoslav Army have been facing an increasing 
number of attempts by Albanian citizens to cross the border 
illegally. Such people are armed, and on several occasions 
armed incidents occurred, resulting sometimes in the wounding or 
death of Yugoslav border guards. 
  "The latest incident, in which Albanian citizen Mustafa 
Ramadan was killed, took place on 3 January this year in the 
region of the border watchtower at Krstac on the territory of 
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia. The mentioned person lost 
his life after he tried to escape, despite warnings given by the 
border guards of the Yugoslav Army," the explanation by the 
information service of the General Staff of the Yugoslav Army 
says in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

