<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serb Official: Latest Muslim Demands Fulfilled </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601181094 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1657 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601181094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Jagodina, 6 Jan (TANJUG) -- Momcilo Krajisnik, 
president of the assembly of the republic of Srpska, stated for 
Jagodina Radio this evening that in talks in Belgrade yesterday 
between Slobodan Milosevic, international mediators Owen and 
Stoltenberg, and representatives of the republic of Srpska, an 
agreement was reached that enables the peace process to be 
brought to an end on 18 January in Geneva. 
  By this, conditions have been created for lifting the 
sanctions against the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, Krajisnik 
said. 
  "The Serb side yesterday confirmed its readiness for Muslims 
to be given 33.3 percent of former Bosnia-Herzegovina territory, 
and accepted a proposal that in the next two years the province 
of Sarajevo, including its nine municipalities, be administered 
by the United Nations, during which time a final solution for 
Sarajevo will be found." 
  "The third thing that we discussed yesterday was our demand 
for access to the sea in the area of Molunat and Prevlaka. The 
last demand by the European Union and the Muslims has been 
fulfilled by our acceptance of the percentage of territory to be 
given to the Muslims and of the status of Sarajevo; therefore 
there is no reason not to abolish the sanctions against the Serb 
people," Krajisnik said. 
  If the negotiations on 18 January in Geneva do not yield 
result, it will be clear that the Muslim side is to blame, 
Momcilo Krajisnik said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

