<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic-Tudjman Talks Open in Bonn </TI></H3>
<H4>   Croatian Proposal Described </H4>
<F P=102> LD1001095794 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
0900 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1001095794 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Jozo Culic in Bonn] </F>
  [Excerpt] The third round of the talks -- initiated by the 
Croats -- began in Bonn at 0900 today [10 January]. Presidents 
Tudjman and Izetbegovic, Croatian Foreign Minister Mate Granic, 
Mile Akmadzic, foreign minister of the Croat republic of 
Herceg-Bosna, and adviser Martic and others are continuing their 
talks on a cease-fire, the delineation of borders, access to the 
sea at Ploce, and mutual Croat-Muslim relations in the future. 
  The details of the Croatian text -- in which Zagreb, we have 
learned from well-informed sources, is seeking 17.5 percent of 
the territory of Bosnia-Herzegovina for the Croats in the Croat 
republic of Herceg-Bosna and is not allowing the Muslims in any 
way to take control of Neum -- have not been made public. 
  Izetbegovic last night agreed in principle to the Croat 
proposal that offers peace, but the Muslims are very tough when 
it comes to the details. It seems that the Muslims have 
objections regarding Mostar; in central Bosnia they are seeking 
to obtain virtually everything for themselves, and access to the 
sea is unresolved as far as they are concerned. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

