<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic-Tudjman Talks Open in Bonn </TI></H3>
<H4>   Accord on Neum, Mostar Cited </H4>
<F P=102> AU1001123894 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1200 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1001123894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Nada al-Isa from Bonn] </F>
  [Text] After a two-day delay the Croatian-Bosnian talks 
are in progress in Bonn. Presidents Izetbegovic and Tudjman are 
discussing three problems: halting the conflict between Croats 
and Muslims in central Bosnia, access to the sea near Neum, and 
the status of Mostar. We have learned from sources in our 
delegation that some new initiatives have been proposed, 
primarily regarding access to the sea near Neum. We have 
learned that, according to the Bosnia-Herzegovina delegation's 
proposal, both Neum and Mostar will be under European control 
for a period of two years. This means in practice that access 
to the sea near Neum will be joint, neither Croatian nor 
Bosnian, but both Croatian and Bosnian. 
  Mostar, like Sarajevo, will be an open city, but under 
European control. Under no circumstances can Mostar be the 
capital of the so-called Herceg-Bosnia or Croatian republic. 
The Croats will be allowed to have the seats of some of their 
(?institutions) in it. However, let me repeat, Mostar will not 
be the capital of the Croatian republic. This means that it 
will formally not be a part of any of the republics in the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina union, but it will belong to everyone. This 
is actually the solution recently proposed in Vienna by Prime 
Minister Silajdzic when he said: Mostar for Mostar's citizens. 
If the European governors manage to organize their authority in 
a satisfactory way, this will mean exactly that: All Mostar 
citizens will be able to return to their Mostar. 
  Let me just mention that, in addition to the two presidents, 
Izetbegovic and Tudjman, the other members of the 
Croatian-Bosnian delegations are Foreign Minister Irfan 
Ljubijankic, Presidency member Ivo Komsic, and Muhamed 
Sacirebey, Bosnia-Herzegovina ambassador to the United Nations, 
on the Bosnian side, and Foreign Minister Mate Granic on the 
Croatian side. The so-called Herceg-Bosnia is being represented 
by Mile Akmadzic. Therefore, Mate Boban is not present. Does 
this mean that a great obstacle to the peace negotiations has 
been removed? Well-informed sources and politicians claim that 
Mr. Boban is already an ex-politician and Zagreb's ex-pet. 
  This has been Nada al-Isa reporting from Germany for Radio 
Television Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

