<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Praises U.S. Stance on East Europe </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0701210394 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
2000 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0701210394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yesterday, in Milwaukee, U.S. Vice President Al 
Gore made a statement in connection with the U.S. President's 
upcoming tour of certain European states and the NATO summit 
meeting to take place in Brussels. 
  We asked the spokesman of Romania's Presidency, Mr. Traian 
Chebeleu, to comment on that statement. Chebeleu said, "we 
learned with interest and satisfaction about the statement made 
by Mr. Al Gore, vice president of the United States of America. 
We consider that statement to be a clear expression of the U.S. 
stance, having the value of a pledge, in the sense of which, 
Romania's security, as well as the security of all other 
countries in this part of Europe, is not indifferent to the 
United States. We consider that statement as a major support for 
the efforts we are making to strengthen the stability and 
security of our country in the context of the convulsions taking 
place in our vicinity and, on a broader plane, to strengthen 
Romania's democratic society." 
  The statement made by the presidential spokesman to our 
radio 
also points out that the position expressed by the U.S. vice 
president responds to our preoccupations and was made in the 
spirit of the recent message addressed by Romania's president to 
the President of the United States and the other heads of states 
that are members of NATO. 

</TEXT>

