<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Walesa Greets U.S. Envoys; Communique Issued </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701173094 Warsaw PAP in Polish 1606 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0701173094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 7 Jan 1994 -- Today President Lech Walesa 
received Madame Ambassador Madeleine Albright, the permanent 
U.S. representative at the United Nations, and General John 
Shalikashvili, the chairman of the Chiefs of Staff of the U.S. 
Armed Forces, the Presidential Press Office reported in a 
communique. 
  Greeting the representatives of President Bill Clinton, 
President Walesa inter alia said: "We owe a lot to the United 
States, we lack the words to express our thanks. It so happens 
that the United States continues to have responsibility for the 
world. We are aware of this great responsibility and we wish to 
talk about this. We will do not wish to hinder these great 
ideas, but we would like to present our stand. 
  A new order is being created in Europe. There is an 
opportunity for a peaceful Europe. There is an opportunity for 
all the models that the United States advocates to be realized 
in their entirety on our continent. As a practical man I know 
that the opportunity that has arisen must be exploited. As a 
soldier I know that the best tactics are small leaps forward. 
It is possible to wriggle forward and sometimes appropriate, 
but observing different fields -- and as a corporal myself I 
trained some people -- I know that the tactic of jumping ahead 
and then crawling forward was always worthwhile. Today I feel 
that there is such an opportunity for a leap in Europe. Of 
course, it is possible to crawl forward, but I do not have to 
prove to soldiers how far slower it is, how far less effective. 
I invite everyone to take part in a discussion, so that we can 
present our arguments," states the communique. 

</TEXT>

