<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cooperation Stressed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801170494 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1500 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0801170494 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] The two special envoys of the U.S. 
President are currently holding talks with Prime Minister Peter 
Boross. Prior to that, the U.S. ambassador to the UN [Albright] 
and the U.S. chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff 
[Shalikashvili] had talks with Defense Minister Lajos Fur and 
Head of State Arpad Goncz. Jozsef Barat reports on the latter 
meeting. 
  [Barat] The Partnership for Peace program is a serious step 
towards political integration rather than being just an ersatz 
[potcselekves], Arpad Gocz said during talks with Ambassador 
Albright and General John Shalikashvili. The terms of the 
complex political and military cooperation program are mutually 
acceptable, the president of the Republic stressed, and he 
called it important that the U.S. initiative treated the region 
as a whole. According to Arpad Goncz, it is also shown by the 
fact that Prague was chosen for the venue of next week's 
meeting. The president agreed that the Partnership for Peace 
program was of extensive and not exclusive character, that is it 
will do no damage, it will not harm sensitive areas in fostering 
ties with the East. 
  President Clinton's special envoys assured Arpad Goncz that 
the security of the United States and that of Central Europe 
were interrelated. For Washington, the security of all 
countries in the region is equally important. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

