<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fur on Military Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801163894 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1500 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0801163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] [Announcer] Hungarian-U.S. talks are underway in 
Budapest on the overseas proposal that NATO should, for the time 
being, only extend its cooperation with the East European 
countries instead of full membership. [passage ommitted] 
  The U.S. President sent two special emissaries to Budapest 
to 
learn about the Hungarian stance on Washington's notion. UN 
Ambassador Albright and General Shalikashvili, U.S. chairman of 
the Joint Chiefs of Staff, first held talks with Minister of 
Defense Lajos Fur. After the meeting Lajos Fur spoke of concrete 
forms of cooperation: 
  [Begin Fur recording] The countries which declare that they 
will accept the system of Partnership for Peace can send 
representatives to NATO headquarters in Brussels. Every country 
will have to decide for themselves whether they take this upon 
themselves, and how much of this they will take on. The 
countries concerned will have to issue a declaration of intent, 
in which they will have to state how much and at what rate they 
wish to take upon themselves the building of relations. To 
continue, representatives can be sent to NATO headquarters in 
Brussels, the same applies to the NATO command, the chiefs, 
where one or two military experts can be sent. 
  Three important fields of concrete military cooperation were 
mentioned: military planning, military training, and the 
organization of joint exercises. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

