<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Albright-Jeszenszky News Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801191694 Budapest MTV Television Network in Hungarian 
1830 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0801191694 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTV Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The international news conference by Madeleine 
Albright and Hungarian Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky ended a 
few minutes ago. Our correspondent Istvan Szelloe reports: 
  [Szelloe] It is no longer a question for Hungary whether we 
will enter NATO, the only question is when, Foreign Minister 
Geza Jeszenszky stressed. Hungary welcomes the Partnership for 
Peace cooperation, and we are of the view that it promotes 
joining the Euro-Atlantic security system. Our foreign minister 
added that relations between our country and NATO had been good 
up to date. The fact that Hungary opened its airspace for AWACS 
planes also proves it. 
  Madeleine Albright, U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, 
conveyed a message from President Clinton, according to which 
Hungary's security is very important for the United States and 
the Partnership for Peace cooperation can lay the foundation of 
security. However, as John Shalikashvili pointed out, it does 
not automatically mean [security]. It is NATO membership that 
can give full security. 
  Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky added: There is virtually 
no 
difference of view in the most important issues between the 
Visegrad countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

