<H3> <TI>   Torgyan's Smallholders Refused Registration </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0601133494 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1100 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0601133494 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] What would Torgyan's Smallholders' Party do if 
put into power? Robert Richard Kiss reports from their news 
briefing: 
  [Kiss] A request for the registration of Torgyan's party has 
been refused, Torgyan himself said at a news briefing. The party 
was formed in order for the electors to clearly see who they are 
voting for in the elections. Just like the Independent 
Smallholders' Party, other parties would also like to get into 
parliament. There would have been only one Torgyan party but, 
following the refusal, it is clear that the Independent 
Smallholders' Party [FKGP] can launch the fight on its own and 
it will not establish an alliance with anybody before the first 
round of the elections, Jozsef Torgyan said. 
  He then talked about the party's foreign political strategy. 
The green light must be given to Asian and Pacific capital, 
because companies from Hong Kong and Taiwan would invest 
billions of dollars in Hungary. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

