<HT>    "dreeu006_c_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-006 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Albright, Shalikashvili Arrive in Prague </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0901182894 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1700 
GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0901182894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Madeleine Albright, U.S. ambassador to the United 
Nations, and John Shalikashvili, chairman of the U.S. Joint 
Chiefs of Staff, arrived in Prague today. Our special 
correspondent Miroslav Konvalina was at the airport. He managed 
brief interviews with them: 
  [Begin recording] [Konvalina] Shortly after 1700, a Boeing 
landed at Ruzyne airport after a flight from Bratislava, 
carrying members of the U.S. Government team responsible for the 
preparation of the coming visit by Bill Clinton to Prague. The 
delegation, which previously had talks in Poland, Hungary, and 
the Slovak Republic, is headed by Madeleine Albright, special 
envoy of the United States for the preparation of the coming 
NATO summit in Brussels, and John Shalikashvili, chairman of the 
U.S. Armed Forces Joint Chiefs of Staff. They were met by Adrian 
Basora, U.S. ambassador to the Czech republic, Alexandr Vondra, 
Czech first deputy foreign minister, and Michael Zantovsky, 
Czech ambassador to the United States. 
  Ambassador Albright then answered only two questions, both 
for Czech Radio. First she said she was expecting from the 
Prague visit agreement on what is necessary for a good summit in 
Brussels and then she said, answering the second question, that 
she did not anticipatate any open questions between the Czech 
Republic and the United States. 
  Before his departure from the airport, General John 
Shalikashvili replied to a question by Czech Radio as to what he 
was expecting from tomorrow's meeting. He said: I look forward 
to it and I expect a lot from it. 
  I asked the general if there were still open questions 
between the Visegrad countries and NATO concerning the 
"Partnership for Peace" initiative. Gen. Shalikashvili replied: 
I am coming with three tasks. First, we want to assure our 
colleagues in Prague that the United States is interested in the 
security of the Czech Republic and its stability. Further, we 
want to hear the views of the hosts and their apprehensions. 
Third, we want to reply to all questions concerning the 
Partership for Peace initiative, which will be discussed at the 
coming summit in Brussels tomorrow. 
  Madeleine Albright and John Shalikashvili have a private 
program tonight. Tomorrow they will meet the Czech prime 
minister, the defense minister, and the foreign minister and 
will leave for Brussels in the afternoon to attend the NATO 
summit, where Madeleine Albright will play a lead role in the 
U.S. presidential delegation. On Tuesday, the two U.S. guests 
will again return to Prague, accompanied by Bill Clinton. 

</TEXT>

