<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Havel Comments on NATO Before Clinton Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0901212394 Prague CT-1 Television Network in Czech 1830 
GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0901212394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CT-1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In connection with the coming visit of U.S. 
President Bill Clinton to Prague, President of the Republic 
Vaclav Havel granted an interview today to Czech Television: 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified interviewer] What program 
and 
what aims will you have at these historical talks? 
  [Havel] The Czech Republic naturally has its views not only 
on the "Partnership for Peace" plan, not only on the future of 
the North Atlantic Alliance, its identity, its position, and its 
meaning, but also on the overall security situation in Europe. 
Naturally, we would like to convey this view to the U.S. side. 
We would be glad if there were a dialogue; we should not just be 
told things. 
  [Interviewer] No one in the West denies that NATO is going 
through an identity crisis. How do you think NATO should solve 
this crisis and, together with it, the question of security in 
Europe? 
  [Havel] NATO has realized that, in the new situation of the 
end of the Cold War, its doctrine, its meaning, its position, 
and its role in Europe have to change, and it has been working 
on it. 
  It may appear from our viewpoint that it has been working on 
it far too slowly, that the situation would require greater 
courage, greater magnanimity, a faster rate. But I think it 
cannot be disputed that this alliance, as the strongest and the 
only functioning one, should be a kind of a stabilizing core of 
all European security. There are differences in the ideas as to 
what technique to use, what speed and so on. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-49302 </DOCNO>
