<H3> <TI>   Klaus To Discuss Security With Clinton </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0701134594 Prague DENNI TELEGRAF in Czech 5 Jan 94 pp 1, 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU0701134594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague DENNI TELEGRAF </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus by Viktor </F>
Krejci; place and date not given: "The Regular DENNI TELEGRAF 
Interview With Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus"] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Krejci] Is it true that the 
Czech side wanted to meet with U.S. President Clinton 
individually but the U.S. side and the other countries of the 
Visegrad Group did not like the idea? 
  [Klaus] When the news first appeared that President Clinton 
would be visiting Prague after the Brussels NATO summit ends, no 
one doubted--and the opposite did not even cross anyone's 
mind--that he would use the visit to Prague to meet with the 
representatives of the governments of all four countries of 
Central and Eastern Europe--that is, the Czech Republic, Poland, 
Hungary, and the Slovak Republic. It was never even considered 
that we would be the only ones to talk with him. On the other 
hand, collective talks have not been considered, either. His 
stopover is simply used for a parallel meeting with four 
delegations. 
  [Krejci] What will be, for the Czech side, the main topic of 
this meeting? 
  [Klaus] The meeting with President Clinton is certainly the 
most important point for us because it is a very important 
signal for the entire world that President Clinton has chosen 
Prague in particular for this meeting between the NATO summit 
and his visit to Moscow. The official talks will be relatively 
brief and the matter of external security will be of greater 
importance because the visit will follow the NATO session. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

