<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Minister on Differences in Group </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701211994 Prague CT 1 Television Network in Czech 1830 
GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0701211994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CT 1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] We had to explain to our partners in Warsaw that the 
Czech Republic intends to join NATO as soon as possible. It does 
not really matter whether this happens jointly or on an 
individual basis. This is what Czech Deputy Defense Minister 
Jiri Pospisil said shortly after his arrival by air from Warsaw. 
  He also explained to the Visegrad defense ministers in the 
Polish capital that our side regards the "Partnership for Peace" 
plan as the maximum of what NATO is able to grant to us at the 
present time. It is also regarded as a minimum designed to 
ensure that security requirements are met. 
  The sides that attended the Warsaw meeting expressed their 
unequivocal consent with Partnership for Peace. However, Deputy 
Minister Pospisil admitted that there are differences as regards 
the considerations regarding the possible coordination of a 
joint approach to NATO. While Poland and Slovakia favor this 
option, Hungary's stance appears to be closer to the Czech 
stance. 
  Polish President Walesa, who met the ministers, pointed out 
that, first and foremost, it should be the Czech Republic that 
should make use of the historical opportunity of joining NATO. 
If it does not do so, Poland will reportedly look for new 
partners. But I do not know which countries he meant, Jiri 
Pospisil said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

