<H3> <TI>   Croat Aggression Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801165394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1549 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0801165394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moslem Radio Sarajevo reported on Saturday that a 
huge column of Croatian military vehicles is leaving from the 
Bosnian Croat-controlled town of Tomislavgrad in western 
Herzegovina and the town of Prozor towards central 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, where fierce Moslem-Croat fighting continues. 
  It is obvious, the radio said, that a big operation is in 
question and that the general staff of the army of neighbouring 
Croatia is involved. 
  Since the beginning of the 21-month-old war in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina over 50,000 regular troops of Croatia's Army 
have fought on the side of Bosnian Croats. 
  Radio Sarajevo also said helicopters of the regular Croatian 
Army have been flying to and fro throughtout the night between 
Friday and Saturday on the course Croatia-western 
Herzegovina-central Bosnia despite the no-fly zone over 
Bosnia-Herzegovina introduced in October 1992 by the United 
Nations. 
  A woman and three children were wounded on Friday in Gornji 
Vakuf in central Bosnia-Herzegovina during Croat fire from 
mortars, howitzers, tanks and multiple-rocket launchers on 
Moslem-controlled parts of the town, the radio said. 

</TEXT>

