<H3> <TI>   Muslims Attacks Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0901193094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1848 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0901193094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratunac, Jan 9 (TANJUG) -- Moslem troops in 
Sarajevo are increasingly using civilian facilities to fire at 
the Serb positions in that city, sources in the Bosnian Serb 
army said on Sunday. 
  The Moslems are firing at us over the positions held by U.N. 
peace-keepers from their strongholds in hospitals, post 
buildings and other exclusively civilian facilities, the sources 
add. 
  The aim is obviously to try to provoke us into neutralizing 
these Moslem nests so that we could then be blamed for attacking 
civilian targets, they explained. 
  The same sources said that the Moslems had used the same 
tactics before to fire at Serb and U.N. positions in Sarajevo, 
the capital of war-torn Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The Serb side has protested with the U.N. Protection Force 
over this practice, but to no avail. 
  Moslem provocations in Sarajevo continue on Sunday, with the 
brunt of the Moslem mortar fire directed at Serb-controlled 
sections of Ilidza, Nedzarici, Grbavica, Dobrinja 4, Vogosca and 
Rajlovac, the Bosnian Serb Army said. 
  Over the past 24 hours, the Moslems were attacking Serb 
military and civilian targets throughout Bosnia-Herzegovina, it 
added. 
  Bosnian Serb troops are firmly holding their positions and 
responding only when absolutely forced to do so, the Bosnian 
Serb army said. 
  It added that the Moslem troops in the Gorazde enclave in 
the 
east continued their attacks on Serb-controlled Foca and Cajnice. 
  Sources in the Bosnian Serb Army also said that, despite a 
U.N. ban on military flights over Bosnia, Moslem helicopters 
were flying from Orasje to Gradacac and Tuzla in northern 
Bosnia, and over the areas of Vares, Breza, Visoko, Kiseljak and 
Vozuce in central Bosnia, where Moslems and Croats have been 
fighting pitched battles since the spring of 1992. 
  The Serb side has duly informed the U.N. command about the 
unauthorized Moslem helicopter flights, the Bosnian Serb 
military sources said and added that the U.N. command had failed 
to react to an earlier warning from the Bosnian Serb command 
that unless such flights stopped, the Bosnian Serb anti-aircraft 
defence would be forced to itself prevent similar incidents from 
recurring. 

</TEXT>

