<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Socialists Lead Early Results of Repeat Vote </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801194394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1828 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0801194394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Jan 8 (TANJUG) -- The final results of the 
early parliamentary election in Serbia show that the ruling 
Socialists have retained the lead, the republican polling board 
said on Saturday after the vote was repeated at 45 polling 
stations. 
  It has been known in advance that the second round of voting 
will in no way shift the balance of forces established after the 
first round of voting held on December 19, because only 0.5 
percent of the voters were asked to cast their ballots for the 
second time. 
  In the 250-seat parliament, the Socialist Party of Serbia 
(SPS) headed by Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic retained 
its 123 seats (49.2 percent). 
  The Democratic Movement of Serbia (Depos), a coalition of 
five opposition parties headed by Leader of the Serbian Renewal 
Movement Vuk Draskovic, is second with 45 seats (18 percent), 
and the Serbian Radical Party (SRS) of Vojislav Seselj third 
with 39 seats (15.6 percent). They are followed by the 
Democratic Party (DS) which won 29 seats (11.6 percent) and the 
Democratic Party of Serbia (DSS) with seven seats (2.8 percent). 
The Democratic Alliance of Vojvodina Hungarians (DZVM), the 
party of the ethnic Hungarian minority in Serbia's northern 
province of Vojvodina, won five seats. A coalition of the Party 
for Democratic Activity and the Democratic Party of Albanians 
won two seats in Leskovac in southern Serbia. The ethnic 
Albanian minority boycotted the election in the southern Serbian 
province of Kosovo-Metohija, where they are the majority 
population. The republican polling board said that 4,300,440 of 
Serbia's 7,010,389 registered voters had turned at the polls, 
and that 1,576,287 of them supported the Socialists and 
2,168,467 the opposition. 
  President of the republican polling board Caslav Ignjatovic 
said that the new parliament should be constituted within the 
next 20 days, or by January 28 at the latest. [Word indistinct] 
Vice-President Goran Percevic said on Saturday that the results 
of the early parliamentary election in which the socialists had 
scored a convincing victory would enable the forming of a stable 
government in the republic of Serbia. 
  Seaking for the local radio in Jagodina, he said, however, 
that the SPS had not yet discussed the possible variants of 
one-party (Socialist) and multi-party governments. 
  It goes without saying that the Socialists would like to see 
a government capable of dealing with the issues of vital 
importance for the citizens of Serbia while the U.N. economic 
embargo is in force and of coming out with a programme of social 
and economic reconstruction after the international blockade has 
been lifted, said Percevic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

