<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Democratic Party Not To Support Coalition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001113794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1112 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001113794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Test] Belgrade, Jan 10 (TANJUG) - The opposition 
Democratic Party (DS) will neither enter a coalition with the 
ruling Socialist Party of Serbia (SPS), nor will it back a 
minority government in the Serbian parliament, the DS main board 
decided. The DS main board said Sunday evening [9 January] it 
would take concrete decisions only if a national unity 
government was being formed. The results achieved at the early 
parliamentary elections in Serbia were also discussed and the 
list of deputies to the parliament adopted. 
  The election campaign was conducted by Zoran Djindjic, the 
president of the DS Executive Committee and head of all DS 
lists. The DS main board discussed the confidence to the 
party's president, Dragoljub Micunovic, but the vote was put off 
until January 15, due to a lack of quorum. The vote on 
confidence to the president of the DS was demanded by 52 
municipal committees, out of a total of 90. 
  At early parliamentary elections, the DS increased the 
number 
of seats compared to last year's parliamentary elections, when 
it won only 7 seats. This year it won 29 seats, to become the 
fourth strongest party in the 250-seat parliament. 
  The SPS won most seats -- 123, but it was below the absolute 
majority line. 

</TEXT>

