<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kovac Considers Decision on RFE `Rash' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0801191794 Bratislava NARODNA OBRODA in Slovak 4 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU0801191794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava NARODNA OBRODA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [TA SR report: "Roman Hofbauer's Rash Decision; Deputy Prime </F>
Minister on the Radio Free Europe Affair"] 
  [Text] Bratislava--In the opinion of Roman Kovac, deputy 
prime minister responsible for media policy, the decision by 
Roman Hofbauer, minister of transportation, communications, and 
public works, to end the operation of the U.S. Radio Free Europe 
[RFE] radio station in Slovakia is rash, and he does not 
consider it fortunate. Minister Hofbauer had not consulted this 
step with him, and he personally learned about it only from the 
press. 
  According to Roman Kovac, the Slovak Government has for some 
time had objections to the legal purity of the contract with the 
RFE, as well as to the nature of its broadcasts. "We do have 
serious reservations about the very small number of listeners of 
this radio station, which uses one of the best radio 
frequencies, reaching practically into Slovakia's every 
village," Roman Kovac stressed. He does not perceive this 
decision as a matter that would interfere with the plurality of 
views, but he believes that it is not good to resort to such a 
sharp step without previous consultations. However, he did not 
rule out that, following the reassessment of all of the aspects, 
the final verdict could be similar to that pronounced by Roman 
Hofbauer. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

