<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ethnic Hungarians Seek New Relationship </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801170694 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1600 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0801170694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1600 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The meeting of mayors and deputies of legislative 
bodies from southern Slovakia opened in Komarno this afternoon. 
Jarmila Tosecka, our editor, will now highlight for us the 
atmosphere of the meeting. 
  [Tosecka] Good afternoon, the meeting in Komarno is at 
present reaching its climax. In the course of the past four 
hours, a number of mayors of towns and villages took their turns 
to make lengthier speeches from the platform, in which they 
appraised the current local government's rights, draft of the 
territorial-administration reorganization, and the 
constitutional position of Hungarians in Slovakia. 
  That part of the meeting's agenda passed calmly, despite 
critical reservations and fundamental proposals on the 
resolution of the problems. The ensuing debate, however, was 
marked by passionate words and statements. 
  At the close, the organizers acquainted the participants in 
the meeting with the content of the open letter they are sending 
to the Slovak president. Apart from other things, they appeal to 
the whole Slovak public with these words: Let us seek a path to 
ourselves but only on the principle of equality. 
  I shall now quote briefly from the final statement adopted 
by 
the participants in the national meeting of members of local 
governments, mayors, and deputies of legislative bodies from 
southern Slovakia in Komarno. The draft is currently being 
presented by one of the organizers: 
  The Central European space is characterized by, among other 
things, unsettled ethnical relations and accumulated tension 
that could lead to tragic conflicts. We shall do everthing 
possible in the interest of ensuring that such a conflict does 
not break out in the Carpathian base. It is, however, necessary 
to point out that ethnical problems must be tackled also here. 
For Slovakia, which gained independence in 1993, this means that 
relations between Slovaks and Hungarians must be built on new 
foundations. In the interest of this, it is necessary to create 
a new system of relations between Slovaks and Hungarians, and it 
is necessary to pass new laws. The steps taken by the government 
to date have contributed to the worsening of mutual relations. 
The new system of relations is to strengthen the basic pillars 
of democracy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

