<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   MOS Wants Minority Issue Institutionalized </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0701153494 Bratislava NARODNA OBRODA in Slovak 5 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU0701153494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava NARODNA OBRODA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by "NO": "Minorities as an Appendix of the State? </F>
Hungarian Civic Party on Slovak-Hungarian Relations"] 
  [Text] Bratislava--The editorial office received a 
statement from the Hungarian Civic Party [MOS] yesterday that 
states, among other things, that what is absolutely lacking is 
an institutionalization of the solution to the problems of the 
national minorities. Quite the contrary, the solution to these 
problems is being transferred to extraparliamentary forums. 
Individual components of power, political parties, and cultural 
and social organizations mutually interfere in their powers. 
  MOS considers it alarming that leading government and 
parliament representatives have endorsed the demands of the 
assembly of Slovaks from southern Slovakia held at Surany on 2 
January, which contain elements that are incompatible with the 
principles of parliamentary democracy and whose spirit and tone 
are reminiscent of the pre-1989 period. MOS does not identify 
with the appeal issued by the Association of Towns and Villages 
of Zitny Island because some parts of the appeal are not in 
conformity with the party's program. 
  The statement observes that present power holders regard 
ethnic minorities merely as an appendix of the state. All 
citizens, including members of the minorities, are a source of 
the sovereignty of the Slovak Republic, and, therefore, they 
rightly demand legal and institutional guarantees of the 
preservation of their distinctive identity. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

