<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Commander Lodges Protest With Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0701191494 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1834 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0701191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, Jan 7 (TANJUG) -- The commander of the 
U.N. troops in ex-Yugoslavia, General Jean Cot lodged a 
complaint with the Croatian authorities over the mistreatment of 
Canadian peacekeepers by the Croatian Army. The UNPROFOR [UN 
Protection Forces] communique, conveyed to TANJUG Friday [7 
January], states that on January 5 seven armed Croatian soldiers 
stopped, disarmed and arrested four Canadian peacekeepers who 
were on a routine patrol in the area of Medak, south of the 
republic of Serb Krajina. 
  The communique adds that the patrol commander had shown his 
authorisation to cross the territory which was ignored and the 
Canadian soldiers were forced at gunpoint to go to the local 
Croatian Army headquarters. Describing the incident as 
"shameful" Jean Cot requested of the Croatian authorities to 
conduct an inquiry and punish those responsible. In an action 
named "Scorched Earth" last September the Croatian Army has 
occupied the Medak area, and burnt down 11 Serb villages and 
brutally murdered 72 civilians. The republic of Serb Krajina 
was declared by the Serbs in 1991 in parts of the former 
Republic of Croatia where Serbs are a majority population, in 
defiance of the forced Croatian secession from the former 
Yugoslavia and their downgrading of the Serbs from a constituent 
nation to a national minority. 
  Although the RSK has been under U.N. protection since March 
1992 in that period Croatia has three times attacked the Serb 
state that it does not recognize, with the aim of forcibly 
placing it under its authority. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

