<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Baudys Rejects Joint NATO Admission Strategy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0601214494 Prague CTK in English 1359 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0601214494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague Jan 6 (CTK) -- There is no reason for a 
coordinated strategy of the Visegrad Four countries (the Czech 
Republic, Slovakia, Hungary and Poland) regarding their 
relations to NATO, Czech Defence Minister Antonin Baudys told 
journalists today. He was reacting to the question whether his 
absence from the Warsaw meeting of the Visegrad defence 
ministers, planned for Friday [7 January], was connected with 
any statements on the agenda of the meeting. 
  Secretary of State to the Slovak Defence Ministry Ivo Urban 
said on Wednesday [5 January] that the defence ministers' 
meeting should coordinate the joint approach to the admission in 
NATO and the joint strategy before its forthcoming meeting. 
  "I refused to attend the first planned meeting already as I 
did not deem it purposeful to work on a joint strategy of the 
Visegrad Four regarding their relations with NATO," Baudys said. 
"The formulation about the joint strategy towards NATO 
countries is very unclear for us," he said. 
  Baudys added that if the Warsaw meeting were to be devoted 
to 
the issue again, he believes that the first deputy minister of 
defence is skilled and informed enough to be able to present the 
views of the ministry. "We do not want to create any new 
groupings," Baudys said. 

</TEXT>

