<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Baudys: Army Cuts `Will Probably Be Halted' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0801173594 Prague CTK in English 2019 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0801173594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague Jan 6 (CTK) -- Czech Defence Minister 
Antonin Baudys today said that further cuts in the Czech Army 
will probably be halted in the near future and that it is 
possible that the role of the Army will grow again. 
  At a press conference, he said this would depend on 
developments in the former Yugoslavia and in southern areas of 
the former Soviet Union as well as on what the political and 
economic consequences of the first democratic elections in 
Russia would be and how they would be reflected in concrete 
steps, given the economic and political stabilisation of the 
country. 
  Baudys said that the reduction of military forces is a 
historical process currently underway in Europe as a result of 
the break-up of the bipolar world. He said it was a natural 
response by certain states but not all of them. In this context 
he mentioned Sweden, which is increasing its army budget, and 
Austria, which is strengthening its anti-aircraft defence. 
  Baudys said that, in his opinion, there should be no cuts in 
the army in future, but rather that its effectiveness should 
increase. Therefore, it is necessary to build effective systems 
of management and command and effective defence systems. But 
this is rather expensive, and "we must take into consideration 
what our budget is," he concluded. 

</TEXT>

