<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jeszenszky Previews Prague Summit Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0701114894 Budapest MTI in English 1006 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0701114894 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] London, 7 January (MTI) -- In many respects, 
Hungary is today much closer to NATO than it was one year ago, 
Hungarian Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky said in an interview 
with the BBC's Hungarian service on Thursday [6 January]. 
  Discussing the forthcoming Prague meeting, Jeszenszky said 
the main aim of the talks is for the new American Administration 
to be familiarized with the views of Central Europe, and for 
Washington to acknowledge that the road to Moscow leads through 
Central Europe. 
  The Prague talks should, according to the foreign minister, 
also focus on the steps that could best promote the survival, or 
intensification of the favorable, democratic processes in Russia. 
  As regards the expansion of NATO, Jeszenszky again stressed 
that opening the organization towards the East would not 
strengthen the conservative forces in Russia. "In my view, the 
contrary of this is true: Expanding NATO is a Russian interest 
as well," he said. 
  Jeszenszky said he does not agree with the position whereby 
the American "Partnership for Peace" proposal conceals the 
intention of delivering Central-Eastern Europe into the hands of 
the Russians. "I consider the existence of such a Western 
intention to be completely out of the question, nor do I believe 
that the American proposal, or any other Western policy, would 
result in this," Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky said. 

</TEXT>

