<H3> <TI>   Pawlak Notes `Indefinite' Program </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801164794 Warsaw PAP in English 1618 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0801164794 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Jan. 8 -- Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak 
told journalists of the regional press during a meeting in 
Warsaw on Saturday that U.S. President Bill Clinton's initiative 
"Partnership for Peace" was indefinite and only the name of the 
program was known. 
  Pawlak added that talks with President Clinton's envoy 
Madeleine Albright on Friday did not result in a declaration 
that the "Partnership for Peace" program would lead to NATO 
membership. According to the prime minister, these are only 
mechanisms enabling Poland to maintain direct military contacts 
for which this country will have to pay. These contacts will 
not function in case of a threat. 
  Pawlak told journalists he had discussed the American 
proposal with Russian Ambassador to Poland Yuriy Kashlev on 
Friday. He said the cabinet would adopt an official stand of 
the Polish Government on this question before the summit of the 
Visegrad group in Prague and talks with President Clinton and 
would do this at the nearest session of the council of ministers 
with the participation of President Lech Walesa and chairmen of 
the Sejm and senate foreign policy committees. 

</TEXT>

