<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Andrejcak Returns From `Useful' Visegrad Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0801182694 Prague CTK in English 2000 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0801182694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava Jan 7 (CTK) -- Today's meeting of 
defence ministers of Poland, Slovakia and Hungary and the Czech 
Republic's first deputy defence minister, held before U.S. 
President Bill Clinton's summit meeting with Visegrad countries' 
representatives in Prague, was very useful, Slovak Defence 
Minister Imrich Andrejcak said today. 
  Speaking to journalists upon his return from Warsaw, 
Andrejcak said that U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations 
Madeleine Albright and Chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of 
Staff John Shalikashvili left the meeting convinced that "it was 
important and advantageous" for them to support cooperation with 
the Visegrad Four (the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary and 
Poland). The Slovak Republic supports cooperation aimed at 
ensuring better security and prosperity, Andrejcak said. 
  He said so-called "contact groups" would be established 
after 
Clinton's Prague visit to study possibilities and ways for 
further cooperation. The next meeting of Visegrad defence 
ministers will be held in Bratislava, he added. 
  He said Czech Defence Minister Antonin Baudys's absence from 
the meeting would not hamper cooperation within the Visegrad 
Group, adding that the deputy Czech defence minister, on behalf 
of the Czech Republic, voiced apprehensions over the possibility 
of the institutionalisation of the Visegrad Group that, 
Andrejcak said, was not being considered by anyone. 
  The participants in the Warsaw meeting discussed the 
American 
Partnership for Peace initiative, which offers them closer 
military links with NATO. 

</TEXT>

