<H3> <TI>   Coalition Meeting Condemns Hungarian Demands </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0701064294 Prague CTK in English 2149 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0701064294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava Jan 5 (CTK) -- The strategy of the 
leaders of Hungarian minority parties in Slovakia is unambiguous 
and will create an atmosphere of mistrust, intolerance and 
hatred among citizens, Slovak Parliament Deputy Chairman 
Augustin Marian Huska said at today's meeting of the coalition 
Movement For a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) and Slovak National 
Party (SNS). 
  "Dreams of a greater, or even of a `middle-sized' Hungary 
cannot be fulfilled," Huska said, adding that it was not 
possible for the government not to have contingency plans in 
case the state should be threatened. He expressed the 
conviction that Slovakia would be able to preserve its 
territorial integrity. 
  Slovak Minister of Culture Dusan Slobodnik said that "there 
is no government more tolerant than the current Slovak one." 
Slovak Deputy Premier Sergej Kozlik called on Slovaks to 
express their dissatisfaction over attempts by the Hungarian 
minority to achieve autonomy in southern Slovakia. 
  "It is time for parliament to consider passing a law on the 
protection of the Republic," Slobodnik said, adding that among 
the Hungarian minority there were still "many decent people who 
want to live peacefully in Slovakia." 
  The worsening of the situation in Slovakia is tied to a 
demand made by the Association of Towns and Villages of Zitny 
Island, which is calling for autonomy for southern Slovakia from 
Bratislava to the Ukrainian border. An assembly to discuss the 
demand is to be held on January 8 in Komarno, southern Slovakia. 

</TEXT>

