<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Campaign Against Komarno Mayor Gathers Support </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0701064094 Prague CTK in English 2152 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0701064094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava Jan 5 (CTK) -- A public rally of several 
hundred citizens of the southern Slovak town of Komarno, 
convened by the Slovak cultural organisation Matica Slovenska in 
its Komarno House today, supported a petition drive for the 
resignation of Komarno Mayor Isztvan Pasztor, a leader of the 
Hungarian minority in southern Slovakia. 
  Pasztor is a chairman of the Council of the Association of 
Towns and Villages of Zitny Island, which has called a meeting 
of deputies and mayors from southern Slovakia designed to 
establish a Hungarian "region with special legal status" in the 
area populated mostly by ethnic Hungarians. 
  Yesterday, a group of Komarno citizens started a petition 
drive for the dismissal of Pasztor, putting up petitions at many 
places in the town. Zdenka Anettova, director of the Komarno 
Matica Slovenska House, told CTK that about 2,000 citizens have 
already signed the petitions, while some 5,000 people are 
required for the mayor to be dismissed. 
  A resolution adopted by the public rally condemned the 
Komarno meeting scheduled for this Saturday [8 January], 
describing it as the "first frank move towards the violation of 
the Slovak Republic's integrity, with the final aim being to 
join Slovakia to Greater Hungary." 
  At the same time, participants appealed to Slovak President 
Michal Kovac to initiate a change in the law on elections to 
local offices. The amended law should guarantee citizens of 
Slovak nationality the right to participate in administration of 
all towns and villages in the Slovak Republic, including in the 
regions where they are the minority. 
  They also called on the Slovak Government to rapidly work 
out 
a "concept of a definitive solution to ethnic minority problems" 
and to submit it to the Council of Europe as a proposal for a 
European norm on the national minority position. 

</TEXT>

