<H3> <TI>   Denies Report on Minority Senate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0801183894 Prague CTK in English 1501 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0801183894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava January 7 (CTK) -- Contrary to 
information which appeared recently in the Slovak press, the 
creation of a hundred-member senate of representatives of the 
Hungarian minority in Slovakia is not at present legally 
justified, Council Chairman of the Association of Towns and 
Villages of Zitny Island Istvan Pasztor said on Slovak Radio 
today. 
  He said that the programme of the meeting of Hungarian 
representatives, to be held in Komarno tomorrow, had originally 
included the establishment of a civic association of elected 
representatives of the Hungarian minority, but the Slovak 
Interior Ministry had said it would not register such a body. 
There was no sense in establishing an body with no legal 
competence, Pasztor said. 
  The meeting was expected to pass a resolution which will 
serve as a basis for the programmes of political parties and for 
further debate in parliament, he said. 
  Tomorrow's meeting is open only to elected representatives 
of 
towns and villages, parliamentary deputies, journalists and 
invited guests, Pasztor said. Representatives from all the 
foreign embassies in Bratislava and from the Council of Europe 
had been invited to the meeting, which would be conducted in 
Hungarian, with translation provided into Slovak and English. 

</TEXT>

